Local family wins Halloween with Ghostbusters costumes, including working Ecto-1!

by Zachary Rogers, WKRC

Local family wins Halloween with Ghostbusters costumes, including working Ecto-1! (Sean Lehmkuhl)

VIEW PHOTO GALLERY

22 photos

CINCINNATI (WKRC) - If there's something strange in your neighborhood, who you gonna call? Ghostbusters!

The Lehmkuhl family of Montgomery revealed their group Halloween costume on social media and it's clear, they ain't afraid of no ghost!

PHOTO GALLERY: SEE HOW HE MADE THE ECTO-1


Their costumes include the iconic Ghostbusters gear, the Stay Puft Marshmallow Man, Slimer, a working mini-Ecto-1 and even a lil' Vigo the Carpathian, complete with painting.


It was Sean Lehmkuhl (the dad) who built the Ecto-1. He says that his 2-year-old and 4-year-old sons watch The Real Ghostbusters 80's cartoon on Netflix and have seen both movies, but that they understand that it's all pretend so they think the ghosts are fun and silly.


"I had all the Kenner Ghostbuster toys as a kid (which were made in Cincinnati) and my brother and I have one of the largest original Star Wars toy collections in the country (They own www.toyhoarders.com which is a whole other story in itself) so I’m a big kid at heart. I love creating costumes every year for them and have been creating costumes for them since our first son was born."

Sean has been creating costumes for his kids for the past few years as well. Last year he made a Batmobile.


The year before that? An X-Wing fighter from Star Wars (Check out the adorable R2D2!).


Here's how Sean said he made this year's Ecto-1. You can see progress photos in our photo gallery:

I started with a Power Wheels Jeep Hurricane vehicle, using a grid and freehanding the Ecto-1, I came up with a good shape with measurements I felt represented the iconic movie prop while allowing me some room to make my own creative tweaks. I used a heat knife then glued and sanded 2” Foamular insulation foam. The whole vehicle can assembled and disassembled in about 15” to transport it. I used flashing LEDs for the lighting on top and the space under the hood is fitted with a Bluetooth speaker system so they can play the Ghostbusters theme as they drive.
